<div id="c3">
<p>&#8220;Free trade is fine for economics departments and newspaper editorials, but nobody in the corporate world or the government takes the doctrines seriously. The parts of the US economy that are able to compete internationally are primarily the state-subsidized ones: capital-intensive agriculture (agribusiness, as it&#8217;s called), high-tech industry, pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, etc.&#8221;</p>

<p>You didn&#8217;t take free trade seriously because you handed out subsidies, undermining free trade.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://question-everything,mahost.org">Joe Licentia</a>
 on June  2, 2006 <a href="#c3" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
