<div id="c28">
<p>Well, with the usual caveat that I have no legal comepetence or qualification, the reasoning seems to me clear enough. Mr Swartz&#8217;s challenge meets all the criteria for a legally enforceable contract. There is &#8216;consideration&#8217; (he offers to pay a reward in return for something of value, i.e. the information that he requires), &#8216;certainty&#8217; (he has stated clearly what it is he requires in order to pay the reward), intention (he did intend to pay up on a successful challenge, and has actually done so in one case) and acceptance (I accepted the challenge). If Mr Swartz had declared his challenge orally it might still be a legally enforceable contract in principle, but difficult to demonstrate in practice. Fortunately there are no such doubts in this case, owing to the admirable clarity with which Mr Swartz stated his challenge. By vanishing when the going got tough, Mr Swartz has indicated the seriousness with which he treats the issue, so I think we can take it he agrees with me rather than you on this.</p>

