<div id="c35">
<p>You&#8217;ve got this the wrong way round. No contract is involved in advertising goods for sale. The contract is created (without signature, and - as happens if you&#8217;re shopping in a supermarket and take your goods to the checkout - witbout necessarily even words) when the buyer offers to buy certain goods and the seller accepts the offer. In Mr Swartz&#8217;s challenge there is consideration: he offers, without conditions attached, to pay a reward for something of value, i.e. the information he has asked for. That meets the criterion of a contract, and as the item of value has been provided, many times over, Mr Swartz appears to be in breach of it. I hazard a guess that this may be why he has vanished.</p>

<p>Instead of continually asserting your incredulity about my point (which I am not legally competent to give, but believe to be true), you might now attend to Russil&#8217;s.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://oliverkamm.typepad.com">Oliver Kamm</a>
 on July 11, 2006 <a href="#c35" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
