<div id="c49">
<p>&#8220;Well then, presumably we agree that the notion that the objectives of the Marshall Plan were to retore the economic health and vigor of Western Europe and to protect it from exploitation by totalitarian movements is as real as the notion that the objectives of Stalinist Russia&#8217;s intervention in Eastern Europe were to protect the majority from elite warmongers and to prevent a fascist takeover of Europe.&#8221;</p>

<p>I know you&#8217;re being sarcastic, but there are indeed Soviet internal documents available now, through the Cold War International History Project, and they do shed light on Soviet motives (and fear of the future revival of German and Japanese militarism was indeed a major motive).   Check this out, for example:
http://www.wilsoncenter.org/topics/pubs/ACFB29.PDF</p>

<p>&#8220;The Allies are Pressing on you to Break your Will&#8230;&#8221;:  Foreign Policy Correspondence Between Stalin and Molotov And Other Politburo Members, September 1945 - December 1946.</p>

